From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] net: ps4_mts v89 - add MT7531 RGMII TX delay (mainline values)

v88 hardware test confirmed deepseek's SlvDPSready bombshell — the PHY-
to-partner handshake is now completely healthy (RF=0, MS_FAULT=0,
both receivers OK).  But linkreg bit 0 still doesn't latch.

Remaining hypothesis: RGMII timing between Baikal MAC and MT7531 PHY
is marginal at POR defaults.  Without proper TX delay (MMD 0x1e regs
0x13/0x14), the MAC's RX from PHY sees corrupted RGMII data, the
PHY's MAC-side electrical interface looks broken, and the PHY never
asserts a stable LINK signal pin -> MAC's link detector stays at 0.

Mainline mt7531_phy_config_init (drivers/net/phy/mediatek/mtk-ge.c:87-94)
writes both TX delay registers with PAIR_B=0x4 and PAIR_D=0x4:

  MMD 0x1e reg 0x13 (MTK_PHY_GBE_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL):
    bits 10:8 = MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_B_MASK = 0x4
    bits 2:0  = MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_D_MASK = 0x4
    => write 0x0404

  MMD 0x1e reg 0x14 (MTK_PHY_TEST_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL): same value 0x0404

v89 adds these as v89(g) after v88(f) and before the final BMCR AN
restart, so AN starts training with proper RGMII timing in place.

Pass criteria for v89 (the hopeful one):

  - dmesg shows "v89(g): TX_DELAY r0x13: 0x???? -> 0x0404"
  - dmesg shows "v89(g): TX_DELAY r0x14: 0x???? -> 0x0404"
  - WITHIN A FEW SECONDS: linkreg transitions to 0x00000b19 or similar
    with bit 0 = 1
  - BMSR latch bit 2 = 1 (link up at PHY)
  - Network connectivity (ping, ssh — though might be on different IP)

If v89 STILL doesn't bring link up: RGMII timing wasn't the issue
either.  Remaining suspect would be MAC's PCS sync requiring actual
data traffic (chicken-and-egg) or a hidden MAC-side PCS register we
haven't found.

Verified against mainline source per CLAUDE.md sanity-check rule:
  - mtk-ge.c:22 #define MTK_PHY_GBE_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL = 0x13 ✓
  - mtk-ge.c:23 #define MTK_PHY_TEST_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL = 0x14 ✓
  - mtk-ge.c:24 MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_B_MASK = GENMASK(10, 8) ✓
  - mtk-ge.c:25 MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_D_MASK = GENMASK(2, 0) ✓
  - mtk-ge.c:87-94 mt7531_phy_config_init writes 0x4 to both pairs ✓
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/sony/ps4_mts.c
@@ -661,6 +661,37 @@
 		}
 
 		/*
+		 * v89 (g): RGMII TX delay - mainline mt7531_phy_config_init sets
+		 * these.  Originally deferred in v88 (deepseek said not link-critical
+		 * for user port), but v88 hardware test showed PHY-level handshake
+		 * succeeds yet MAC's BAR+0x04 bit 0 won't latch.  Suspicion: RGMII
+		 * timing between Baikal MAC and MT7531 PHY is marginal at POR
+		 * defaults, causing PHY's MAC-side RX to see corrupted data and
+		 * never assert a stable LINK signal.
+		 *
+		 * MMD 0x1e reg 0x13 (MTK_PHY_GBE_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL):
+		 *   bits 10:8 = MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_B_MASK = 0x4
+		 *   bits 2:0  = MTK_TX_DELAY_PAIR_D_MASK = 0x4
+		 *   => 0x0404
+		 *
+		 * MMD 0x1e reg 0x14 (MTK_PHY_TEST_MODE_TX_DELAY_SEL): same value.
+		 */
+		if (mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0x13, &v16) == 0) {
+			u16 nw = (v16 & ~((0x7u << 8) | 0x7u)) | (0x4 << 8) | 0x4;
+			mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0x13, nw);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v89(g): TX_DELAY r0x13: 0x%04x -> 0x%04x (PAIR_B=4 PAIR_D=4)\n",
+				 v16, nw);
+		}
+		if (mts_smi_c45_read(mts, 0x1e, 0x14, &v16) == 0) {
+			u16 nw = (v16 & ~((0x7u << 8) | 0x7u)) | (0x4 << 8) | 0x4;
+			mts_smi_c45_write(mts, 0x1e, 0x14, nw);
+			dev_info(&mts->pdev->dev,
+				 "v89(g): TX_DELAY r0x14: 0x%04x -> 0x%04x (PAIR_B=4 PAIR_D=4)\n",
+				 v16, nw);
+		}
+
+		/*
 		 * FINAL AN restart per Orbis (BMCR |= 0x1200).  This is the LAST
 		 * thing we do so AN starts training with all corrections applied.
 		 */
